Next month will mark 8 years that we made the move from Charlotte to Charleston. Since the kids didn’t have school, we decided to do something Wheeler and Effie haven’t done since we moved here. We walked the bridge! It’s still hard to believe that they’ve never done it. We’ve gone under it in our boat a gazillion times, I’ve made many runs over it (including many Bridge Runs) and I’ve taken the boys up it on many stroller rides. But today, all four of them walked it and it was a beautiful day. Little did we know that when we got home, we saw on the news that Arthur Ravenel Jr. (whom the bridge was named after) passed away just yesterday. My dad that went to The Citadel and MUSC will agree, he’s very thankful for the new bridge’s construction compared to the old Cooper River Bridge. As a past avid runner, I will always be thankful for a little bit of elevation here in the Lowcountry.

So proud of my Wheeler Bea at her STEM Interactive Museum Showcase! Such a cool experience! Her light shines when it comes to her love and joy of learning. I’m so glad she could share a glimpse of it with us last night! As a mom, I know I’m a little biased 😉, but it was also so warming to hear the praise from her teachers. ❤️

In more details from her teachers about the exhibit: Over 118 students came together in their English Language Arts & Social Studies classes and researched a topic of their choosing about America’s journey to, through, and beyond the American Revolution with an emphasis on South Carolina’s important role in the war. They studied museum exhibits and text features, as well as components that are integrated into interesting and interactive museum displays. Using our STEM Fab Lab and under the guidance of our pre-engineering department, students not only created a trifold teaching visitors about their topic, but also created an interactive STEM component that furthers the learning . From building websites and apps, to engineering with cardboard and plastic, to wiring LED lights, to coding touch screens, and even making 3D printed replicas, our students challenged themselves to engineer and build some pretty amazing museum exhibits. Visitors to the museum will walk chronologically through the events and people that make up the founding of our great country! The project was funded in part by a generous grant from the South Carolina chapter of the Daughters of the American Revolution and we are honored and grateful for their assistance and kindness.

We got into Boston yesterday afternoon thinking we’d show the kids a little of the Freedom Trail while we were here. Maybe visit an Irish pub? Our plans changed quickly when we started on our walk to the Old North Church. I noticed some guys wearing Red Socks jerseys and mentioned to Lanier that they might have a home game. Fast forward to deciding to go to the game, getting tickets and and grabbing an Uber - we were at Fenway before the first pitch! Had we planned on going, I wouldn’t have worn what I had on. But since it was impromptu, I was fine being the only person wearing super bright colors to a Red Sox game. Imagine my surprise when we walked in and saw that their uniforms were the exact same colors as what I was wearing! What are the odds? 😂 Found out later they were inspired by the Boston Marathon colors. Needless to say, I fit right in.

Have to add that Lanier and I are huge Braves fans and had always thought their first MLB game would be in Atlanta, but we knew we couldn’t pass up this opportunity. And boy did it pay off! The weather couldn’t have been more beautiful. We had all the things - ice cream, pretzels, cotton candy, cracker jacks, tried all the beer, watched a proposal, did the wave and sang Sweet Caroline at the top of our lungs! But the best part happened in the 9th inning. The game was tied at the bottom of the 9th and the bases were loaded. Pablo Reyes hit a walk-off grand slam to win it! And he not only hit a grand slam, it hit the foul pole! 🙌🏻 Couldn’t have had a better time at Fenway!

Boston was a blast! Now on to the next city!

Hard to narrow it down to just 10 photos, but DC was a blast! Kind of wish we’d split it up into two days since there was so much to see, but I also feel like it was cool to see so much. Wheeler will start high school. She’s got her permit and has already taken her driving class and loves to practice driving. She’ll continue piano and tennis and still enjoys her friends and youth group. She’s a little sad since a lot of her friends will be going to another school, but I have no doubt she’ll find ways to keep in touch with them and make new ones this year too. She is such a great example to her siblings and has an awe-inspiring love of learning. Praying she has teachers this year that will keep that spark alive. It’s going to be a big adjustment with just how large and busier everything will be, but I’m trusting in Him that the school will make her feel welcome and comfortable.

Effie will continue theater in her troupe’s Senior Company which will require more hours of technique and rehearsals, but she is so excited! She really wanted to continue piano and tennis, but sadly there’s just not enough time to fit it all in. So she had to stop piano, but on the days when she’s not rehearsing, she wants to continue tennis. She’ll also start Confirmation at church.

Logan will start middle school! He’s a little nervous to switch classes, but thankfully Effie will be there. She’s already insisted on walking him to class on the first day and showing him where to go…although he insists he already knows. Love his confidence. He’s going to try and follow in his sisters’ footsteps and try out chorus. I’d say he loves to sing, but let’s be real, he’s really doing it for all the fun trips. This year he changed what he wants to be when he grows up from something other than NASCAR. Not sure if this is a serious turn or he’s just really excited to start back tennis.

This will be Vaughn’s first year not having a sibling with him at school, but I know he’ll be fine. He’ll continue tennis, with his true love being nature, animals, anything outside and hanging with friends. Hoping he’ll be eager to knock out his schoolwork quickly so he’ll have plenty of time to enjoy that every afternoon.

Here’s to a fresh new start and exciting new beginnings! 🩷
